%pyspark

from matplotlib.ticker import LinearLocator, FormatStrFormatter
from matplotlib import cm

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import tensorflow as tf
import numpy as np

import time

%pyspark

# === Create some fake data

# Set a seeded random value
np.random.seed(0)

# Create an array of inputs between -10 and 10 with a step of 0.3
inputs = np.arange(-10, 10, 0.3)

# Obtain the size of the input array
total_input_size = inputs.shape[0]

%pyspark

# We can see that we have linear data from -10 to 10
plt.plot(inputs)
plt.show()
plt.close()

%pyspark

# Use Numpy to create a sine wave out of our range of data
sine = np.sin(inputs)

%pyspark

# Now we can see that we have a sine wave!
plt.plot(sine)
plt.show()
plt.close()

%pyspark

# === Data is never perfect though, let's add some noise of the Gaussian persuassion

# This will create the actual noise to be used
noise = 0.15 * (np.random.randn(total_input_size))

%pyspark

# Our noise looks like so
plt.plot(noise)
plt.show()
plt.close()

%pyspark

# We can add the noise to our sine wave with the following
noisy_sine = sine + noise

# We can use this as the target for our model
targets = noisy_sine

%pyspark

# Let us see what our new sine wave looks like
plt.plot(targets)
plt.show()
plt.close()

%pyspark

# === Now we will need to split up our data
# === There are a lot of ways to do this splitting, we will use Numpy for consistency

# We start by randomly selecting some data (this will be 20% of our total data)
selected_randomly = np.random.randint(0, high=total_input_size, size=int(0.2 * total_input_size))

# We make sure to keep track of what wasn't selected as well
not_selected_randomly = [j for j in range(total_input_size) if j not in selected_randomly]

%pyspark

# We also would like our training set. This comes from whatever data was not randomly selected.
train_inputs = inputs[not_selected_randomly]
train_targets = targets[not_selected_randomly]

%pyspark

# No we can specify our validation set from our randomly selected data
validation_inputs = inputs[selected_randomly]
validation_targets = targets[selected_randomly]

%pyspark

# === We can also create a test set
# === This will be a closer to what an actual sine wave should look like (normally we don't have this)

# This is similar to what we did previously (with a difference in step size)
test_inputs = np.arange(-10, 10, 0.025)
test_targets = np.sin(test_inputs)

%pyspark

# Let us take a look at the test data (notice it is a little more well rounded that before)
plt.plot(test_targets)
plt.show()
plt.close()

%pyspark

# We need to make sure the Numpy vectors will fit into TensorFlow
# Therefore we need nx1 matrices (the data remains unchanged)

# Transformation for training data
train_inputs = np.expand_dims(train_inputs, 1)
train_targets = np.expand_dims(train_targets, 1)

# Transformation for validation data
validation_inputs = np.expand_dims(validation_inputs, 1)
validation_targets = np.expand_dims(validation_targets, 1)

# Transformation for test data
test_inputs = np.expand_dims(test_inputs, 1)
test_targets = np.expand_dims(test_targets, 1)

%pyspark

# We will actually verify that the data hasn't changed at all
plt.plot(test_targets)
plt.show()
plt.close()

%pyspark

# === From Lesson 2, let's build the graph first

# Let's specify some hyper-parameters
number_of_hidden_neurons = 5
input_size = 1
output_size = 1

%pyspark

# We build the graph here!
g = tf.Graph()

with g.as_default():
    
    # Specify a seed for random values
    tf.set_random_seed(1)

    # We create "None" size placeholders to let us put variable sized "Batches" of data at a time
    x = tf.placeholder("float", shape=(None))
    y = tf.placeholder("float", shape=(None))
    
    # We're going to use an initializer to generate random values for our weights
    initializer = tf.contrib.layers.xavier_initializer()
    
    # Hidden layer weights, connecting input to hidden neurons
    hidden_weights = tf.Variable(initializer(shape=[input_size, number_of_hidden_neurons]))
    
    # Output layer weights, connecting hidden neurons to output
    output_weights = tf.Variable(initializer(shape=[number_of_hidden_neurons, output_size]))
    
    # Biases for the hidden neurons
    bias1 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros([number_of_hidden_neurons]))
    
    # Biases for the output 
    bias = tf.Variable(tf.zeros([output_size]))
    
    # Hidden layer logits and activation function
    hidden = tf.nn.tanh(tf.matmul(x, hidden_weights) + bias1)
    
    # Output layer 
    output_layer = (tf.matmul(hidden, output_weights) + bias)
    
    # Squared Error error function
    error = tf.reduce_mean(tf.pow((y-output_layer), 2))
    
    # We will use Adam Optimizer for network optimization
    optimizer = tf.train.AdamOptimizer().minimize(error)
    
    # Our initialization operation
    init = tf.initialize_all_variables()

%pyspark

# Make sure any previous plot is closed
plt.close()

# Do everything we can to make sure the plot is interactive
z.configure_mpl(angular=True, close=False)
plt.ion()

# Create the session
# We don't do a Session with block due to some matplotlib shenanigans
sess = tf.Session(graph=g)
sess.run(init)
    
# Training loop
for i in range(1000):
    
    # Show our progress every 100 steps
    if i % 100 == 0:
        test_output = sess.run(output_layer, feed_dict={x: test_inputs})
        plt.clf()
        plt.axis([-10,10,-2,2])
        plt.plot(test_inputs, test_targets, label='True Signal')
        plt.plot(test_inputs, test_output, label='Model Output')
        plt.plot(train_inputs, train_targets, '+', label='Training Data Points')
        plt.legend()
        plt.show()
        plt.pause(0.001)
        
    # We actually train here (note that we call 'optimizer')
    sess.run(optimizer, feed_dict={x: train_inputs, y: train_targets})
    
    # Get the error values and print them out
    if i % 100 == 0:
        validation_error = sess.run(error, feed_dict={x: validation_inputs, y: validation_targets})
        training_error = sess.run(error, feed_dict={x: train_inputs, y: train_targets})
        print i, '- Validation Error:', validation_error, 'Training Error:', training_error
      
# Show final error on test set
testing_error = sess.run(error, feed_dict={x: test_inputs, y: test_targets})
print 'Testing Error:', testing_error

# Make sure the session is closed
sess.close()
